\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Armor can be welded or otherwise fixed securely to a mecha\rquote s superstructure, providing an equipment bonus to the mecha\rquote 
s Defense. Mecha armor does not impose a maximum Dexterity bonus upon the mecha operator (as worn armor does) and does not require a special proficiency feat to use.
\par Installing armor on a mecha requires a Craft (mechanical) check (DC 20). The check is made after investing an amount of time determined by the mecha\rquote s size: Large 3 hours, Huge 6 hours, Gargantuan 12 hours, and Coloss
al 24 hours. Armor can be removed in half the time with a successful Repair check (DC 20).
\par Different types of mecha armor are presented below, along with the following statistics:
\par }{\b Equipment Bonus: }{The equipment bonus that the armor provides to the operator\rquote s Defense.
\par }{\b Armor Penalty: }{Mecha armor applies this penalty on its operator\rquote s Balance, Climb, Escape Artist, Hide, Jump, Move Silently, and Tumble checks.
\par }{\b Speed Penalty: }{The amount by which the armor reduces the mecha\rquote s base speed.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{The cost of the armor.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{Since mecha require a license to own and operate, mecha armor does not require a special license to purchase.
\par }{\b 
\par ALUMISTEEL ARMOR (PL 5)
\par }{This easy-to-acquire alloy is lightweight and reasonably strong. Alumisteel can also be used as a building material for mecha superstructures (see Mecha Superstructure, above).
\par }{\b Equipment Bonus: }{+5.
\par }{\b Armor Penalty: }{\endash 6}{\b .
\par Speed Penalty: }{\endash 5 feet}{\b .
\par Purchase DC: }{10 + one-half the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\b 
\par DURAPLASTIC ARMOR (PL 5)
\par }{Duraplastic armor is made of advanced plastic polymers, such as carbon fiber and high-grade fiberglass. Although relatively cheap and light, it doesn\rquote t offer tremendous protection.
\par }{\b Equipment Bonus: }{+3.
\par }{\b Armor Penalty: }{\endash 4}{\b .
\par Speed Penalty: }{None}{\b .
\par Purchase DC: }{5 + one-half the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\b 
\par DURALLOY ARMOR (PL 6)
\par }{Duralloy is harder, heavier, and more durable than alumisteel. It can also be used as a building material for mecha superstructures (see Mecha Superstructure, above).
\par }{\b Equipment Bonus: }{+8.
\par }{\b Armor Penalty: }{\endash 8}{\b .
\par Speed Penalty: }{\endash 10 feet}{\b .
\par Purchase DC: }{10 + one-half the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\b 
\par RESILIUM ARMOR (PL 6)
\par }{Resilium is a more malleable alloy than duralloy, although not as strong.
\par }{\b Equipment Bonus: }{+6.
\par }{\b Armor Penalty: }{\endash 5}{\b .
\par Speed Penalty: }{None}{\b .
\par Purchase DC: }{5 + one-half the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\b 
\par CRYSTAL CARBON ARMOR (PL 7)
\par }{Grown in orbital laboratories, crystal carbon is a composite fiber material that narrowly outperforms neovulcanium (see below) on the battlefield.
\par }{\b Equipment Bonus: }{+10.
\par }{\b Armor Penalty: }{\endash 8}{\b .
\par Speed Penalty: }{None}{\b .
\par Purchase DC: }{15 + one-half the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\b 
\par NEOVULCANIUM ARMOR (PL 7)
\par }{Similar to duralloy, neovulcanium uses plasma-forging techniques to create an alloy of surprising resilience. It is also used as a building material for mecha superstructures (see Mecha Superstructure, above).
\par }{\b Equipment Bonus: }{+10.
\par }{\b Armor Penalty: }{\endash 10}{\b .
\par Speed Penalty: }{\endash 5 feet}{\b .
\par Purchase DC: }{10 + one-half the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\b 
\par MEGATANIUM ARMOR (PL 8)
\par }{Sandwiched layers of crystal carbon and neovulcanium held in a magnetic matrix, megatanium is exceedingly hard and durable. It can also be used as a building material for mecha superstructures (see Mecha Superstructure, above).
\par }{\b Equipment Bonus: }{+12.
\par }{\b Armor Penalty: }{\endash 10}{\b .
\par Speed Penalty: }{\endash 10 feet}{\b .
\par Purchase DC: }{10 + one-half the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\b 
\par REACTIVE ARMOR (PL 8)
\par }{Consisting of layers of insulating gel or compressed gas between cerametal sheets, reactive armor provides the same protection as crystal carbon armor but is considerably cheaper and easier to produce.
\par }{\b Equipment Bonus: }{+8.
\par }{\b Armor Penalty: }{\endash 5}{\b .
\par Speed Penalty: }{None}{\b .
\par Purchase DC: }{5 + one-half the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\i 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel1\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {MECHA EQUIPMENT
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Mecha equipment falls into several categories: flight systems, sensor systems, defense systems, weapons (both hand-he
ld and integrated), and miscellaneous systems.
\par Installing a piece of equipment on a mecha\emdash be it a weapon or some other integrated system\emdash requires a Craft (mechanical) check (DC 20). The check is made after investing an amount of time determined by the mecha\rquote 
s size: Large 10 minutes, Huge 30 minutes, Gargantuan 1 hour, Colossal 3 hours. If the weapon or system occupies more than one equipment slot on the mecha, multiply the installation time by the number of slots it takes up. An integrated weapon or system 
can be removed in half the time with a successful Repair check (DC 20).
\par In addition to a general description, each piece of equipment includes the following information:
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{The number of equipment slots needed to install the equipment. Some pieces of equipment are limited to specific body slots, as noted here.
\par }{\b Activation: }{How long it takes to activate the piece of equipment (usually an attack action).
\par }{\b Range/Range Increment: }{A range listing indicates the maximum distance out to which the equipm
ent functions. If a range increment is listed instead, it represents the distance at which accuracy begins to decline, as per the rules on range increments.
\par Unless otherwise noted, equipment with a range increment has a maximum of ten increments.
\par }{\b Target or Targets/Effect/Area: }{
This entry starts with one of three headings: Target, Effect, or Area. If the target of the component is You, you do not receive a saving throw (and there is no saving throw entry for the piece of equipment). If a component is a weapo
n capable of autofire, it will be noted here.
\par }{\b Duration: }{The amount of time a piece of equipment continues to operate before it needs to be reactivated, or how long its effect lasts. A duration of persistent means the equipment functions until the mecha is 
destroyed (reduced to 0 hit points) or the mecha\rquote s operator turns it off (usually as a free action). 
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{If a piece of equipment calls for a saving throw, the type of saving throw is listed here, along with the effect of a successful save.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{The purchase DC for the Wealth check to acquire the equipment.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{The level of license required to purchase the equipment legally.
\par }{\fs24 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\ql \li0\ri0\keepn\widctlpar\faauto\outlinelevel1\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {Leave Room for the Pilot
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {When equipping a mecha from scratch, make sure to leave at least two vacant equipment slots for the mecha operator\rquote 
s cockpit. (The cost of the cockpit is already factored into the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.) On Large mecha, the operator always occupies two of the following three equipment slots: helmet, torso, and back. On Huge and bigg
er mecha, the designer has more choice when placing the operator\rquote s cockpit.
\par Copilot and passenger cockpits are described under Miscellaneous Equipment.
\par }{\fs24 
\par MECHA FLIGHT SYSTEMS
\par }{All mecha are equipped with legs that allow them to walk and run. A mecha\rquote s size d
etermines its base speed, as noted in Table: Mecha Sizes. This section describes various optional flight systems. To build a flight system from scratch, a character must succeed at a Craft (mechanical) check (DC 30) after investing 60 hours in its assembl
y. A character without a mechanical tool kit takes a \endash 4 penalty on the skill check. The character must also make a Wealth check against the flight system\rquote s purchase DC.
\par }{\b 
\par AFTERBURNER SYSTEM (PL 6)
\par }{The afterburner system dumps a shot of raw fuel into the mecha\rquote s thruster system, giving the mecha a temporary speed boost. The mecha\rquote 
s fly speed is doubled for 1 round. The afterburner system is good for only one use; additional activations require additional afterburner systems.
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1, must be torso, back, or leg.
\par }{\b Activation: }{Free action.
\par }{\b Range: }{Personal.
\par }{\b Target: }{You.
\par }{\b Duration: }{1 round.
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{8 + one-quarter the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\b 
\par JETPACK (PL 6)
\par }{A jetpack combines vectored thrust with simple avionics, granting the mecha a fly speed of 100 feet (clumsy). The jetpack carries enough fuel for the mecha to travel a total of 1,000 feet; refueling has a purchase DC of 16.
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1, must be back or boots; or 2, must be left leg and right leg.
\par }{\b Activation: }{Free action.
\par }{\b Range: }{Personal.
\par }{\b Target: }{You.
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent.
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{10 + one-quarter the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\b 
\par JET-ASSIST WINGS (PL 7)
\par }{Jet-assist wings allow a flying mecha to maneuver more effectively, but do not provide the mecha with the ability to fly. A mecha with jet-assist wings improves its flight maneuverability by one category (clumsy to poor, poor to average, and so on).

\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1, must be back or shoulders (Large or Huge); 2, must be back or shoulders (Gargantuan or Colossal).
\par }{\b Activation: }{None.
\par }{\b Range: }{Personal.
\par }{\b Target: }{You.
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent.
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{5 + one-quarter the mecha\rquote s purchase DC.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\b 
\par THRUSTER BOOTS (PL 7)
\par }{Thruster boots combine powerful fusion thrusters to give the mecha a fly speed of 150 feet (poor).
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1, must be boots.
\par }{\b Activation: }{None.
\par }{\b Range: }{Personal.
\par }{\b Target: }{You.
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent.
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{10 + one-quarter the mecha\rquote s purchase DC.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\b 
\par RAMJET THRUSTER BOOTS (PL 8)
\par }{The best thruster system available uses ramjet technology to improve the performance of the PL 7 thruster boots, granting the mecha a fly speed of 200 feet (poor).
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1, must be boots.
\par }{\b Activation: }{None.
\par }{\b Range: }{Personal.
\par }{\b Target: }{You.
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent.
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{10 + one-quarter the mecha\rquote s purchase DC.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\fs24 
\par MECHA SENSOR SYSTEMS
\par }{Sensor systems make it easier for mecha operators to perceive their surroundings; however, not all mecha are equipped with sensors (or even require them). In such cases, mecha operators must rely on their own acute vision and hearing.
\par A mecha equipped with sensors conducts passive scans of the surrounding area constantly, without the operator\rquote 
s attention. A passive scan extends in all directions at once, providing the operator with data on surrounding terrain, obstacles, and the location of other creatures, vehicles, and mecha within several miles of the mecha\rquote s position.
\par A sensor system can also be used to conduct an active scan of a single target. With a successful Computer Use check (DC 15) and a move action, a mecha\rquote 
s operator can use the onboard sensor system to actively scan a single nonliving target (usually another mecha or vehicle) and determine specific information about that target, as specified in the sensor system\rquote s description.
\par To build a sensor system from scratch, a character must succeed at a Craft (electrical) check (DC 30) after investing 60 hours in its assembly. A character without an electrical tool kit takes a \endash 
4 penalty on the skill check. The character must also make a Wealth check against the sensor system\rquote s purchase DC.
\par }{\b 
\par CLASS I SENSOR SYSTEM (PL 6)
\par }{This sensor system includes air/space radar that allows a mecha operator to scan the basic topography of the surrounding area and pick out targets well enough to aim weapons at them. A Class I sensor system grants a +2 equipment bonus on the operator
\rquote s Navigate and Spot checks.
\par With a successful Computer Use check (DC 15) and a move action, the operator can use the sensor system to actively scan a single nonliving target (usually another mecha or vehicle) and determine all the following information about that target:
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s size.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s locomotive capabilities.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s present direction or trajectory.
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1.
\par }{\b Activation: }{Move action (active scan mode only).
\par }{\b Range: }{1-mile-radius emanation centered on your mecha.
\par }{\b Area: }{1 nonliving target (active scan only).
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent (passive scan mode) or 1 round (active scan mode).
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{18.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\b 
\par CLASS II SENSOR SYSTEM (PL 6)
\par }{This sensor system includes an electromagnetic (EM) detector array that localizes electromagnetic emissions, and an infr
ared detector that tracks targets by their heat signatures. It also incorporates a high-resolution video system that differentiates targets by their visual profile. The hi-res video system incorporates a zoom feature, allowing close inspection of distant 
targets. A Class II sensor system grants a +2 equipment bonus on the operator\rquote s Navigate and Spot checks.
\par With a successful Computer Use check (DC 15) and a move action, the operator can use the sensor system to actively scan a single nonliving target (usually another mecha or vehicle) and determine all the following information about that target: 
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s size.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s locomotive capabilities.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s present direction or trajectory.
\par \bullet  The number of living creatures aboard, if applicable.
\par \bullet  The composition of the target\rquote s hull or superstructure, as well as the type of its armor, if any.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s weapon systems (functional and nonfunctional).
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1.
\par }{\b Activation: }{Move action (active scan mode only).
\par }{\b Range: }{1-mile-radius emanation centered on your mecha.
\par }{\b Area: }{1 nonliving target (active scan only).
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent (passive scan mode) or 1 round (active scan mode).
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{21.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\b 
\par CLASS III SENSOR SYSTEM (PL 6)
\par }{This system combines the features of the Class II sensor system with an advanced night-vision unit.
\par The mecha operator gains darkvision to a range of 90 feet. A Class III sensor system also grants a +2 equipment bonus on the operator\rquote s Navigate and Spot checks.
\par With a successful Computer Use check (DC 15) and a move action, the operator can use the sensor system to actively scan a single nonliving target (usually another mecha or vehicle) and determine all the following information about that target:
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s size.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s locomotive capabilities.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s present direction or trajectory.
\par \bullet  The number of living creatures aboard, if applicable.
\par \bullet  The composition of the target\rquote s hull or superstructure, as well as the type of its armor, if any.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s weapon systems (functional and nonfunctional).
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1.
\par }{\b Activation: }{Move action (active scan mode only).
\par }{\b Range: }{1-mile-radius emanation centered on your mecha.
\par }{\b Area: }{1 nonliving target (active scan only).
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent (passive scan mode) or 1 round (active scan mode).
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{25.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{Licensed (+1).
\par }{\b 
\par ENIGMA SENSOR SUITE (PL 6)
\par }{Using a combination of thermal imaging, X-rays, and vibration sensors, the Enigma sensor suite enables the operator to effectively see through solid objects. Fine details can\rquote 
t be detected, but a mecha using the Enigma suite could tell, for example, that three Medium-size humanoids were crouched behind a closed door, or that an escape tunnel runs from one building to another.
\par A mecha with the Enigma suite reduces the effects of concealment by two grades. Thus, an object with total concealment (50% miss chance) would have three-quarters concealment (30% miss chance) instead.
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1.
\par }{\b Activation: }{None.
\par }{\b Range: }{150 feet.
\par }{\b Area: }{Cone-shaped emanation.
\par }{\b Duration: }{1 round.
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{29.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\b 
\par ORACLE TARGETING SYSTEM (PL 6)
\par }{The standard computer-assisted targeting system for mecha combines holographic displays and heuristic target-prediction profiling to increase a mecha operator\rquote 
s accuracy. The system grants an enhancement bonus on attack rolls (+1 to +5) when using a specific ranged weapon selected by the operator. Switching the bonus from one weapon to another requires a move action.
\par The Oracle system has five different categories (denoted Mark I through Mark V). The purchase DC varies depending on the enhancement bonus conferred.
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1, must be helmet or visor.
\par }{\b Activation: }{Move action (to activate or switch).
\par }{\b Range: }{Personal.
\par }{\b Target: }{You.
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent.
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{16 for Mark I (+1), 18 for Mark II (+2), 20 for Mark III (+3), 22 for Mark IV (+4), 24 for Mark V (+5).
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\b 
\par CLASS IV SENSOR SYSTEM (PL 7)
\par }{This system includes electromagnetic (EM),
 infrared detector, hi-res video, and nightvision sensors similar to those found on the Class II and Class III systems. It also incorporates a ladar system that uses low-powered laser beams to quickly locate and identify difficult terrain, distant obstacl
es, and targets.
\par The mecha operator gains darkvision to a range of 120 feet. A Class IV sensor system also grants a +4 equipment bonus on the operator\rquote s Navigate and Spot checks.
\par With a successful Computer Use check (DC 15) and a move action, the operator can use the sensor system to actively scan a single nonliving target (usually another mecha or vehicle) and determine all the following information about that target: 
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s size.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s locomotive capabilities.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s present direction or trajectory.
\par \bullet  The number of living creatures aboard, if applicable.
\par \bullet  The composition of the target\rquote s hull or superstructure, as well as the type of its armor, if any.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s weapon systems (both functional and nonfunctional).
\par \bullet  How much damage (in hit points) the target has taken.
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1.
\par }{\b Activation: }{Move action (active scan mode only).
\par }{\b Range: }{10-mile-radius emanation centered on your mecha.
\par }{\b Area: }{1 nonliving target (active scan only).
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent (passive scan mode) or 1 round (active scan mode).
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{27.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{Licensed (+1). }{\b\fs17 Oracle Targeting System
\par }{\b 
\par CLASS V SENSOR SYSTEM (PL 7)
\par }{This system improves upon earlier sensor systems by replacing the air/space radar with powerful multiband ra
dar that quickly and effortlessly identifies and tracks mecha, creatures, and vehicles. It also combines the electromagnetic, infrared, and video scanners into a single, more powerful array. The Class V sensor system also extends the mecha\rquote 
s nightvision capability.
\par The mecha operator gains darkvision to a range of 180 feet. A Class V sensor system also grants a +6 equipment bonus on the operator\rquote s Navigate and Spot checks.
\par With a successful Computer Use check (DC 15) and a move action, the operator can use the sensor system to actively scan a single nonliving target (usually another mecha or vehicle) and determine all the following information about that target:
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s size.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s locomotive capabilities.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s present direction or trajectory.
\par \bullet  The number of living creatures aboard, if applicable.
\par \bullet  The composition of the target\rquote s hull or superstructure, as well as the type of its armor, if any.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s weapon, defense, and sensor systems (both functional and nonfunctional).
\par \bullet  How much damage (in hit points) the target has taken.
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1.
\par }{\b Activation: }{Move action (active scan mode only).
\par }{\b Range: }{10-mile-radius emanation centered on your mecha.
\par }{\b Area: }{1 nonliving target (active scan only).
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent (passive scan mode) or 1 round (active scan mode).
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{30.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{Licensed (+1).
\par }{\b 
\par CLASS VI SENSOR SYSTEM (PL 8)
\par }{This sensor system resembles the Class V sensor array, except that it replaces the multiband radar unit with multiphase radar capable of penetrating nearly any obstacle or barrier.
\par The mecha operator gains darkvision to a range of 180 feet. A Class VI sensor system also grants a +8 equipment bonus on the operator\rquote s Navigate and Spot checks.
\par With a successful Computer Use check (DC 15) and a move action, the operator can use the sensor system to actively scan a single nonliving target (usually another mecha or vehicle) and determine all the following information about that target:
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s size.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s locomotive capabilities.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s present direction or trajectory.
\par \bullet  The number of living creatures aboard, if applicable.
\par \bullet  The composition of the target\rquote s hull or superstructure, as well as the type of its armor, if any.
\par \bullet  The target\rquote s weapon, defense, and sensor systems (both functional and nonfunctional).
\par \bullet  How much damage (in hit points) the target has taken, and how much damage it can withstand (that is, hit points remaining).
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1.
\par }{\b Activation: }{Move action (active scan mode only).
\par }{\b Range: }{100-mile-radius emanation centered on your mecha.
\par }{\b Area: }{1 nonliving target (active scan only).
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent (passive scan mode) or 1 round (active scan mode).
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{32.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{Licensed (+1).
\par }{\fs24 
\par MECHA DEFENSE SYSTEMS
\par }{Defense systems include energy shields, life support systems, and other equipment intended to protect the mecha and its operator from harm.
\par To build a defense system from scratch, a character must succeed at a Craft (mechanical) check (DC 30) after investing 60 hours in its assembly. A character without a mechanical tool kit takes a \endash 
4 penalty on the skill check. The character must also make a Wealth check against the defense system\rquote s purchase DC.
\par }{\b 
\par BULWARK TACTICAL SHIELD (PL 5)
\par }{The Bulwark tactical shield\emdash a high-tech version of the shields carried by knights of old\emdash is worn on one of the mecha\rquote s arms. It improves the mecha\rquote s equipment bonus to Defense by +4.
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1, must be arm.
\par }{\b Activation: }{None.
\par }{\b Range: }{Touch.
\par }{\b Target: }{You.
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent.
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{5 + one-quarter the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\b 
\par BASTION TACTICAL SHIELD (PL 6)
\par }{The Bastion tactical shield improves upon the Bulwark tactical shield (see above). It improves the mecha\rquote s equipment bonus to Defense by +6.
\par When not deployed, the Bastion tactical shield can retract into the mecha\rquote s arm. Deploying or retracting the shield is a move action.
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1, must be arm.
\par }{\b Activation: }{None or move action (see text).
\par }{\b Range: }{Touch.
\par }{\b Target: }{You.
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent.
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{5 + one-quarter the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\b 
\par LX-10 ANTISHOCK ARRAY (PL 6)
\par }{The LX-10 antishock array grounds the mecha and protects it against electrical attacks. The mecha gains electricity resistance 10.
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1.
\par }{\b Activation: }{None.
\par }{\b Range: }{Personal.
\par }{\b Target: }{You.
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent.
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{21.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\b 
\par BARRICADE TACTICAL SHIELD (PL 7)
\par }{A larger version of the Bastion tactical shield, the Barricade shield not only improves the mecha\rquote s equipment bonus to Defense by +8, but its superior ceramic coating grants the mecha fire resistance 10.
\par When not deployed, the Barricade tactical shield can retract into the mecha\rquote s arm. Deploying or retracting the shield is a move action.
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1, must be arm.
\par }{\b Activation: }{None or move action (see text).
\par }{\b Range: }{Touch.
\par }{\b Target: }{You.
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent.
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{8 + one-quarter the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\b 
\par DELPHI DEFENSE SUITE (PL 7)
\par }{The Delphi defense suite consists of a heuristic collision avoidance system, enhanced crew restraints, and a series of adrenal and nonadrenal autoinjectors for the mecha operator. The Delphi defense suite grants the operator a resi
stance bonus on all saving throws for 1 minute: +1 for the Mark I version and up to +5 for the Mark V version.
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1 (Mark I and Mark II versions), 2 (Mark III, Mark IV, and Mark V versions).
\par }{\b Activation: }{Attack action.
\par }{\b Range: }{Personal.
\par }{\b Target: }{You.
\par }{\b Duration: }{1 minute.
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{21 for Mark I (+1), 23 for Mark II (+2), 25 for Mark III (+3), 27 for Mark IV (+4), 29 for Mark V (+5).
\par }{\b Restriction: }{None.
\par }{\b 
\par LIGHT FORTIFICATION (PL 7)
\par }{The mecha\rquote s structural integrity is reinforced so it can shake off attacks that would cripple it otherwise. Light fortification converts 25% of all critical hits into regular hits.
\par Installing  light fortification requires a Craft (structural) check instead of a Craft (mechanical) check. Light fortification takes the place of one of the mecha\rquote s equipment slots.
\par }{\b Equipment Slots: }{1 (equivalent).
\par }{\b Activation: }{None.
\par }{\b Range: }{Personal.
\par }{\b Target: }{You.
\par }{\b Duration: }{Persistent.
\par }{\b Saving Throw: }{None.
\par }{\b Purchase DC: }{10 + one-half the mecha\rquote s base purchase DC.
\par }{\b Restriction: }{Licensed (+1).
\par }{\b 
\par LX-20 ANTISHOCK ARRAY (PL 7)
