\par MISCELLANEOUS EQUIPMENT
\par }{This section describes various other pieces of mecha equipment that don\rquote t fall neatly under the other categories, including a variety of electrical systems.
\par Building a system from scratch requires a character to make a Wealth check against the system\rquote s purchase DC, invest time in its assembly, and succeed at a Craft (electrical), Craft (mechanical), or Craft (structural) check (DC 30)\emdash 
whichever seems most appropriate given the type of equipment. See the Craft skill description for further guidance. A character without the appropriate electrical or mechanical tool kit takes a \endash 4 penalty on the skill check.
\par }{\b 
\par COCKPIT, COPILOT (PL 5)
\par }{This extra cockpit provides a comfortable station inside the mecha for a Small or Medium-size copilot. A copilot has the ability to fire the mecha\rquote s ranged weapons, perform active scans using the mecha\rquote s sensor systems, or aid the pilot
\rquote s attacks and skill checks (using the aid another action). Melee combat, defense, and movement remain under the control of the mecha\rquote s operator in the main cockpit. A copilot doesn\rquote 
t grant the mecha additional attacks in a round, and only one character may fire each ranged weapon each round. The mecha operator or copilot can transfer weapon control as a free action.
\par As a move action, the mecha\rquote s operator can lock out one or more copilot cockpits, shutting off the cameras, locking the hatches, and so on.
\par It takes a successful Computer Use check (DC 25 if the operator is disabled, 35 if the operator is still active) to switch overall control of the mecha to a copilot cockpit.
